{"cursor":"28994","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Altitude' or 'height' is defined based on the context in which it is used\n(aviation, geometry, geographical survey, sport, and more). As a general\ndefinition, altitude is a distance measurement, usually in the vertical or \"up\"\ndirection, between a reference datum and a point or object. The reference datum\nalso often varies according to the context. Although the term altitude is\ncommonly used to mean the height above sea level of a location, in geography the\nterm elevation is often preferred for this usage.\n\nVertical distance measurements in the \"down\" direction are commonly\nreferred to as .\n","linknr":419,"url":"Altitude","recorded":1362505560,"links":51,"instances":["environmental","geodesy","ecology","biology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Aerospace","Physical geography","Topography"],"headings":["Altitude in aviation and in spaceflight","Altitude regions","High altitude and low air pressure","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Vertical_distances.svg/300px-Vertical_distances.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["datum","geodesy"],["morphology","biology"],["productivity","ecology"],["hypoxia","environmental"]],"members":["hypoxia","datum","productivity","morphology"],"related":["Datum_(geodesy)","Geography","Elevation","Mean_Sea_Level","Pressure_altitude","Flight_level","Transition_altitude","Inches_of_mercury","Altimeter","Atmospheric_pressure","QNH","Above_Ground_Level","Mean_sea_level","QNH","Mean_sea_level_pressure","International_Standard_Atmosphere","Air_pressure","Earth's_atmosphere","Troposphere","Equator","Stratosphere","Mesosphere","Thermos